FORM TAGS:-
<form action = "">
# By using the <form> tag only nothing will be displayed. But when we write,
<form>
<input >
</form>
Then a box will be displayed in the output.

LABLE TAG:-

<label for = "name">First Name</label><br>
The attribute of the <label> tag should be equal to the id attribute of the <input> tag to bind them together.

INPUT TAGS:-
<input placeholder ="" type = "" name ="" required id="" value="">
# placeholder = the name which is seen inside the box and the label is usedfor leabelling the box.
# type will define the type of the input value and the validation too. For example,
<input type="email"> will validate the text only with @ symbol.
# You should always giev the type value for the inputs else all the inputs will be given "text" value as default.
# required will validate that the input box is filled with the values.
# type = "text" for text, "radio" for radio button(sleecting one of many choices), "checkbox" for checkbox(selecting zero or more options), "submit" for submit button, "button" for clickable button.
# type = "date, time, range for selecting range, password, tel for phone number"
# name implies the place where it is to be stored in the backend. This field is mandatory for backend based storing.  For example,
<input placeholder ="First Name" type = "text" name ="Fname" required>

RADIO BUTTON:-
In case of Radio Button, it is used for selecting only one option. Hence the name field should be the same in every <input> tag else we'll be able to select all the available options.
<input type="radio" name="tech" value="html" id="html_id">
<label for="html_id">HTML</label>
<input type="radio" name="tech">
<label>CSS</label>
<input type="radio" name="tech">
<label>JS</label>
Now you'll be able to select anyone of them, if you don't add the name field then you can select all of them.

CHECKBOX BUTTON:-
For checkbox button you can write different names for the name field.
<input type="text" name="tech1" id="tech_id">

FIGURE TAG:-
<figure>
  <img src="pic_trulli.jpg" alt="iALTERNATE TEXT style="width:100%">
  <figcaption>CAPTION</figcaption>
</figure>

FORM FIELD SET:-
<form action="/where to go">
  <fieldset>
    <legend>TEXT LIKE NAME OF THE FORM</legend>
    <label for="fname">First name:</label>
    <input type="text" id="fname" name="fname"><br><br>
    <label for="lname">Last name:</label>
    <input type="text" id="lname" name="lname"><br><br>
    <label for="email">Email:</label>
    <input type="email" id="email" name="email"><br><br>
    <label for="birthday">Birthday:</label>
    <input type="date" id="birthday" name="birthday"><br><br>
    <input type="submit" value="Submit">
  </fieldset>
</form>

FOR EXAMPLE:-
<form action="/action_page.php">
  <fieldset>
    <legend>Personalia:</legend>
    <label for="fname">First name:</label>
    <input type="text" id="fname" name="fname"><br><br>
    <label for="lname">Last name:</label>
    <input type="text" id="lname" name="lname"><br><br>
    <label for="email">Email:</label>
    <input type="email" id="email" name="email"><br><br>
    <label for="birthday">Birthday:</label>
    <input type="date" id="birthday" name="birthday"><br><br>
    <input type="submit" value="Submit">
  </fieldset>
</form>

TEXTAREA TAG:-
<textarea  name="message"  rows="4"  cols="50"  placeholder="Type your message here..."  required  maxlength="500">
</textarea>

*************CSS*************

CSS are of two types:-
~ INLINE CSS
~ INTERNAL CSS
~ EXTERNAL CSS

~INLINE CSS:-
# This is the type of style where you style the tag by writing the features as attributes in the tag itself.
# <section style="background-color: #fffff; color: #333; margin: 20px; padding: 20px; border: 2px;

~ INTERNAL CSS:-
# This is done by the help of <style> tag. The tag will be written within the <head> tag section. For example:-
<head>
 <style>
    body{
      color: #3fff;
      background-color:#ffffff;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 2px;
    }
</style>
# We assign each of like id and class for each tags and write the styling inside the style tag for the speicific ones.
# For id we can just write as follows: classname{} and for classnames we can write as follows: .classname{}
# id can be used when there is a need to select individually.
# class can be used when we'll have to style multiple elements with the same style.

~EXTERNAL CSS:-
# This type is done by creating another external file and writing the contents in them.
<link rel="stylesheet" href="./style.css">
# In external css, we can make use of the id's assigned for each tags.
